 growth and rise in income levels, questions remain as to the general quality of life during this era. Was the improvement in income widely shared? How did economic growth affect the nature of work? Did higher levels of income lead to improved health and longevity? The authors address these questions by analyzing new estimates of labor force participation, real wages, and productivity, as well as of the distribution of income, height, and nutrition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCost and standard of living -- United States -- History -- 19th century -- Congresses. 0aUnited States -- Economic conditions -- To 1865 -- Congresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aindustrialization, standards of living, antebellum, economy, growth, income, quality life, work, health, longevity, history, economics, nutrition, height, wealth distribution, productivity, real wages, labor force participation, capital stock, inequality, prices, class, manufacturing, innovation, invention, technology, agriculture, northeast, massachusetts, market integration, colonial, consumer behavior, nonfiction.1 aGallman, Robert E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallman, Robert E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMargo, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothenberg, Winifred B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSokoloff, Kenneth L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoltow, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteckel, Richard H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWallis, John Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWallis, John Joseph, eeditor.4edt4ht